    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819-05-03_page01.jpg"/>
                    <dateline>
                        <date when="1819-05-03">May 3<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> 1819
                            12 o clock P.M.
                            <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Kensington-Gore_ENK">Kensington Gore</placeName></date></dateline>
                 
          
                    <p>
                    <note>194</note>
                        Now that every thing is packed up &amp;<lb/>
                        ready to put into the carriage I may <choice> 
                        <orig>in..<lb/>
                        dulge</orig>
                        <reg>indulge</reg>
                        </choice>
                        myself in scribbling a few lines<lb/>
                        to my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">mother</persName><lb/></p>
                    <p>
                        Little dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF1">Francis</persName> is with us &amp; we are<lb/>
                        all going together to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#High-Wycombe_ENK">High Wycombe</placeName> - a fine<lb/>
                        day - the carriage will be open - <del>for</del> the first<lb/>
                        7 or 8 miles <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> will ride with <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WhitS1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi><lb/>
                        S Whitbread</persName> and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF1">F</persName> will be in the open<lb/>
                        carriage between her and I - delighted we are<lb/>
                        to have him - after wards George will <choice> 
                        <orig>smug..<lb/>
                        gle</orig>
                        <reg>smuggle</reg>
                        </choice>
                        him up in the seat behind &amp; we can<lb/>
                        talk to him over the head. <choice><orig>NB</orig><reg>Nota Bene</reg></choice> two grown<lb/>
                        up people have sat in it before therefore do<lb/>
                        not imagine it will not hold him<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                        <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WhitE1">Lady EW</persName> just now took me down to her<lb/>
                        own room to ask me whether she might<lb/>
                        have <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF1">Francis</persName> here at any time when we<lb/>
                        are gone. " Whenever it should happen to<lb/>
                        be inconvenient to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Capt<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>. B</persName> or his other<lb/>
                        relations to have him remember I shall<lb/>
                        like to have him here - Before I had seen<lb/>
                        him I would not have asked any school<lb/>
                        boy to stay in my family I sh.<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> have feared<lb/>
                        the charge. But he is such an amiable<lb/>
                    
                        <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819-05-03_page02.jpg"/>
                        amiable creature as well as so intelligent<lb/>
                        and so able to occupy &amp; to take care of <choice> 
                        <orig>him<lb/>
                        self</orig>
                        <reg>himself</reg>
                        </choice>
                        that it will not be a charge but a pleasure<lb/>
                        to me to have him at any time &amp; for any time<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                        I thanked for you with all the warmth<lb/>
                        with which I know you will feel this -<lb/>
                        <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WhitE1">Lady E W</persName> is exceedingly fond both of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName><lb/>
                        &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">Honora</persName> &amp; is certainly sorry to part with<lb/>
                        us. She does not absolutely refuse to come<lb/>
                        to see us in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> tho she says she is<lb/>
                        not yet equal to it . <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GranX2">Miss Grant</persName> wishes it<lb/>
                        for <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WhitE1">Lady E</persName> as well as for herself - and her<lb/>
                        youngest son <add><persName ref="./Personography.xml#WhitS2">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. SW</persName></add> would delight in it - As I am<lb/>
                        in the habit of inviting people to other <choice> 
                        <orig>peo-<lb/>
                        ple's</orig>
                        <reg>people's</reg>
                        </choice>
                        houses I must say that I wish <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lovell</persName><lb/>
                        &amp; you would write to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WhitE1">Lady E W</persName> expressing<lb/>
                        a desire to see her &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GranX2">Miss Grant</persName> &amp; <del>M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. S</del><lb/>
                        Either of her sons who could accompany<lb/>
                        her. - I know she would be gratified . We<lb/>
                        read to her your account of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lovell's</persName> <choice> 
                        <orig>sherif<lb/>
                        =alty</orig>
                        <reg>sheriffalty</reg>
                        </choice>
                        - the jail - the Judge's just <del><choice> 
                        <orig>compli=<lb/>
                        ment</orig>
                        <reg>compliment</reg>
                        </choice></del>
                        praise of the High Sheriff of the C<hi rend="superscript">y</hi> of<lb/>
                        <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Longford_IE">Longford</placeName> . She was much pleased and<lb/>
                        from this &amp; various circumstances has<lb/>
                        a great desire to know <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lovell</persName> - You she<lb/>
                        loves from seeing you reflected in your<lb/>
                        <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">child</persName> &amp; your <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1" cert="medium">child in law</persName> &amp; your <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1" cert="medium">brother</persName><lb/>
                        &amp; little <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF1">son</persName> . She says she thinks she could<lb/>
                        be more at ease <unclear>at</unclear> <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworths Town</placeName> than any<lb/>
                        where but in her own <unclear>home &amp; family</unclear><lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819-05-03_page03.jpg"/>
                    <p><note>195</note>
                        <gap></gap><unclear>spoken</unclear> of<lb/>
                        When <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CarrX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Carr</persName> was telling a story of a dog he asked <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF1">F.</persName> if he knew<lb/>
                        (A) ^<add>what was</add> mean<add>t</add> by instinct? = F<hi rend="superscript">s</hi> answered<lb/>
                        I mean a power which animals possess not<lb/>
                        derived from <del>experience</del> reason nor to be <choice> 
                        <orig>im<lb/>
                        proved</orig>
                        <reg>improved</reg>
                        </choice>
                        by experience<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                        I do not think <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StewD1">Dugald Stewart</persName> or <del><persName ref="./Personography.xml#NewtI1">Newton</persName></del> <add><persName ref="./Personography.xml#LockJ2">Locke</persName>Locke</add> c<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> have<lb/>
                        worded it more exactly - and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CarrX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.</persName> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CarrX3">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. &amp; Miss Carr</persName><lb/>
                        aver that this is word for word his answer.<lb/>
                        <add>spoken of</add><lb/>
                        </p>
                
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819-05-03_page01.jpg"/>
                <p>     Many answers which <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF1">Francis</persName><lb/>
                        makes to the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CarrX4">Carr's</persName> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MarcX1">Marcets</persName> &amp;c when they<lb/>
                        ask him questions! <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CarrX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Carr</persName>told him a curious<lb/>
                        story of a dog - I said, I think this is more<lb/>
                        than we c<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. call instinct. = What do you<lb/>
                        (A)<lb/></p>
                    
                 
                <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819-05-03_page04.jpg"/>
                
                
                
            </div>
        </body>
        <back> </back>
    </text>
